Title: Generalized Macros
Description:
I‚Äôve been writing a lot of Janet lately, and I‚Äôve been especially enjoying my time with the macro system.
Janet macros are Common Lisp-flavored unhygienic gensym-style macros. They are extremely powerful, and very easy to write, but they can be pretty tricky to get right. It‚Äôs easy to make mistakes that lead to unwanted variable capture, or to write macros that only work if they‚Äôre expanded in particular contexts, and it can be pretty difficult to detect these problems ahead of time.
So people have spent a lot of time thinking about ways to write macros more safely ‚Äì sometimes at the cost of expressiveness or simplicity ‚Äì and almost all recent languages use some sort of hygienic macro system that defaults to doing the right thing.
But as far as I know, no one has approached macro systems from the other direction. No one looked at Common Lisp‚Äôs macros and said ‚ÄúWhat if these macros aren‚Äôt dangerous enough? What if we could make them even harder to write correctly, in order to marginally increase their power and expressiveness?‚Äù
So welcome to my blog post.

Title: Range Encoding for Data Compression
Description:
Range encoders are a type of entropy encoder used in modern day data compressors. They're an
evolution of earlier entropy encoders (most notably Huffman encoding) which were restricted to
encoding data as a whole number of bits. Range encoding, by contrast, allows us to encode in
fractions of a bit and thus achieve compression ratios very close to optimal.
